I don't know if someone is going to read this but from pigeon 'till the end of the video I was sobbing. Not because I was sad or to release tension, but because for the first time I noticed it was over. The war was over, the self hatred, all the abusive relationships and friendships, all the self destructive behaviors, the need for external validation, the nights I spent crying because I am the way I am. All my hard work all the promises I made to myself, they worked. Two years ago I wanted to take my life, I hit the rock bottom. Now, I have a regular practice of yoga for a year, I am getting to know this little person inside me, which is me, and they are really fun, I am even eating healthy, something I havent done in my entire life. I started taking care of myself and loving it, taking care of this little child that sometimes didn't have the attention they needed. And what a nice, creative, funny and magical kid I have inside me! Day by day, I was getting better, and being able to do more and more. One day, after months of working on myself, getting myself out of this rock bottom, I felt I was mentally and physically strong enough to do yoga. Next month I will celebrate a year of ywa, with all the highs and lows, all the days I didn't have the energy to get out of bad and do it, I still kept going when I could. Some days you have to be patient and loving and just stay in bed healing. But it's been a year! And it has helped me so much to know myself and accept where I am right now.
Today I just cried out of happiness, in pigeon pose, with my hands connected to the earth, because after two years of recovering, of re-building everything this world destroyed inside me, and I helped the world destroying, after all that work, I realized it was over and I would never be like that again. I WILL commit new mistakes, but now even when I feel alone, I have this little one inside to take care of. I hugged myself lying on my back and cried with a smile in my face, saying to myself: "see? do you see how far did we come? I'm so proud, so so proud of you, I love you". And a saw a perfectly blue sky through my window and I knew it was over. The war against myself, you know. 
And I hope that everyone that took time to read that can feel like that as well.

Hi Adriene and all fellow lovers of everything Adriene - I just wanted to take a moment to express my immense gratitude for you and this community. I would like to share with you my personal story to show you the impact that you have had in my life. My own personal journey has seen me through some very severe depression, anxiety, and a recent bipolar diagnosis. I have been cycling through meds trying to find the right one for me. I have a therapist. I do the work. Through my healing journey you have been a consistent thread. I have completed 2 of your 30 day challenges and I have practiced along side so many of your videos. You rock. I used to live in Austin and had to move to Houston to be closer to family to heal. You connect me back to a city that I love and bring so much positive beautiful energy and share it with this world. 3 years ago I completed my studies Yoga Teacher Training and studies in Ayurveda in Rishikesh and almost become a yoga teacher myself. I even started a business in Austin to bring Ayurveda and the knowledge of India to our Austin community. My personal life and my personal work had other plans for me and while that never fully came to fruition I continue my own personal practice and you are such a big part of it. Thank you Adriene for being one of the most authentic teachers I have found and authentic humans on youtube. Today was a really hard day for me but I found myself looking forward to my practice with you as I always do. The time flies and I leave with more love and gratitude in my heart than when I stepped onto the mat. So from the bottom of my heart - thank you. - your student Divya

I have never commented before, but I really have to thank you, Adriene, from the bottom of my heart. I know you are constantly flooded with notes of gratitude, and so even if mine falls into the abyss of lost letters, knowing that I sent you a bit of gratitude for the way you have changed my life means everything to me. Honestly, I am often plagued by mild cases of built-up anxiety that lead to procrastination as I lose touch with myself. It's always been hard for me to stick to anything, whether it's healthy eating habits or exercise regimens. Yoga, on the other hand, has inspired positive change within my life, without the dread or lack of self compassion that accompanies overly intense discipline. I remember the first session of yoga I ever experienced, about three years ago, which just so happened to be a part of your series for beginner's. I didn't understand how much I'd fall in love with the practice when I first began, as early on I was often brought to tears for reasons I still don't completely understand. All I know is that I was beating myself up and bottling up my feelings. Now, facing my inner truth, it's hard for me not to smile when I feel the sensations and flushes of energy that are so signature to the practice. Whenever I fall out of a regular exercise, I always end up coming back to yoga, where I can release my baggage and let go of festering negativity. I realize how I tend to handle my emotions with impulsiveness and ignorance, and now I have been given the tools I need to show myself love and listen to my heart. But I couldn't have done it without you, Adriene! Nothing compares to your evident warmhearted and genuine personality. Every day when I arrive at the mat I am sure to be invited to a comfortable place where mindfulness, understanding, and kindness are put first. You always share beautiful words of wisdom, as well as random bits of humor that always make me laugh! I cannot believe I am still here, but I am, and this is my fourth 30 days of Yoga experience with you. Lots of Love!!!
All I need to say is NAMASTE!

I have wanted to say this for a while and never know which video to comment on. So I’ll do this one since I did it today. Try and make it short. Grew up in ballet, nearly 5 years  ago snapped all the ligaments in my ankle, could do nothing. Have always had some depression and anxiety issues but medication  didn’t help much and side effects were awful. Earlier this year in February I lost my baby at 15 weeks after trying for 4 years to have a baby. My friend has been telling me to try yoga with you forever, I tried before my ankle was ready but after my miscarriage I started doing yoga everyday. Because of yoga I am functional after this miscarriage. I feel like a new person. More energy since I was a child. No anxiety, WAAAAY less depression, I get out of bed everyday to do yoga to help me function for my other kids. Nothing hurts anymore! You, and yoga have changed my life and made it livable. Thank you. I wish there was a stronger word for it! We ❤️❤️❤️ Adrienne in our house.

I'm in Christchurch at the moment and I've been feeling increasingly saddened by the shooting that took place last Friday. I went to sleep really upset last night and woke up feeling the same. I almost didn't get out of bed to do yoga, but in the end I talked myself into it. I felt a little bit better after doing this video, as I always do after hearing Adriene's encouraging voice, but honestly, I feel so much happier after reading everyone's comments. To anyone feeling bad because they missed a day or they didn't bring a happy mind to the mat on this occasion - don't be so hard on yourself. You are a beautiful, fluid, changing thing. Each day and each experience is going to be unique. And if you missed a day, so what. There's so many more days to come. Yoga seems like it's about the movement but it's really about the mind. Take care everyone and enjoy the journey. This community is a beautiful thing and I'm very grateful for it. Namaste, x

I've been practicing yoga irregulary for about 7 years but I never stick with it for a long time. It's usually 2-3 months and then I slowly cease to do it anymore - because I'm busy, tired or lazy - and it usually takes me about 4-6 six  months to start over. Every single time when I need to start over, I'm angry at myself that I was not able to continue before because there is always a voice in my head during the practice telling me "You managed to do this before" or "You used to be better at this". Even when I'm struggling, I try to be kind to myself but it is not always easy. However, today for a very first time I realized that this time I focus more on how I do things, how I perform every position and I think it is great even if I used to be better at doing that position like two years ago. I'm very grateful for these videos and your kindness and attitude! ❤️

I actually ended up doing 2 videos today because even after finishing day 11 my body said I needed more. As I kept going my body just started feeling better and better, and I felt like I could do a little more with each breath I took. Just before Adriene said we were going to do one-legged pigeon it clicked that that's what my body was really craving and I when she said it I just smiled and thought "I'm already on my way there because you've taught me how to listen to my body", when I came out of pigeon and started rocking and rolling into corpse I felt my body saying it needed a shoulder stand too. When I finally came to corpse pose the only way I can describe how my body felt, and still feels now, is like warm butter just this wonderful warm supple feeling through every ligament. I was in a horrible place physically and mentally when I decided to try yoga 4 years ago and I'm so incredibly grateful that Adriene's site is the first one I found, I know I wouldn't have kept coming back if I had found any of the other instructors I've seen since starting this journey. Because of Adriene's mantra of "find what feels good" I've learned to listen to my body and to step away when I need to. I've lost some toxic people through this awakening and I couldn't be more grateful, I'm excited to see where this journey takes all of us who's lives she has touched.

I agree that we are in control of our own happiness but only to an extent. It’s important to remember that racism, sexism, etc. are very real elements that are deeply woven into the culture - at least in the USA. Many people struggle and suffer as a result of these systems and it’s important not to blame someone because they are poor, or addicted or whatever. In other words, this idea is important but should come with the caveat that many things are beyond our control and being unhappy or anxious or whatever is a natural and human response. No one should feel as though they’ve failed or are inadequate if they’re not happy 100% of the time. Our culture is a bit obsessed with finding happiness to the point where we might feel like any other emotion is wrong or bad. Sorry for the rant but it’s an issue that’s close to home and I saw someone who commented that they felt badly and then felt guilty. Food for thought is all... I am so very thankful for finding you Adriene. It has been almost two years following your videos. I have learned so much. It has been such a ride and experience learning yoga through you. 3 years ago I was diagnosed with an autoimmune thyroid disorder and finding you in the process of healing has been such a blessing. I have learned to look inward more and not focus solely on body image and such. My idea has morphed and it still changes and unfolds. I used to find people would keep a way from me and I always wondered “what am I doing wrong?” and then something changed. I know it is positivity and I recognize with my personality type that I can be alone when need be. That it is okay. I am who I am and everything is unfolding. My chiropractor told me at my last visit, “I love hearing your new discoveries of better health. When I think of you I think, ‘ooh what is next’” It puts a new perspective on where I am. It sheds light and I am grateful of the process. Thank you.

I just want to take the time to thank you for this beautiful chance to practice yoga with you and millions of other people around the world. You are my greatest teacher. You have taught me so much. And the importance here is not that your teachings are definite; they are merely tools to apply to different situations occurring in different times in your life. And I now recognize how I can use them in each situation and ADAPT them.

Teaching us to move with intention is probably the most vital part of this journey. What we radiate is what we feel and what the world will feel from us. And I have noticed such a difference in my mind since I became aware of this. Thank you for teaching us mindfulness and self love in secret while we're holding on to plank for dear life. Thank you for always focusing on what should feel good. Thank you for helping us to challenge ourselves when we think we can't do it. Thank you for lighting that inner smile and inner light in that dark space. Thank you for always being there. Thank you for supporting EVERYONE and acknowledging EVERYONE. Thank you for pointing out that we are all welcome. Thank you for turning our homes in to a safe and calm spot where we can be ourselves and maybe along the way finding the courage to take it outside in to the world as well.

Lots of love and gratitude from me to you, you wonderful soul. Have an amazing day and thanks for reading this. <3
